---
title: 'Kindness Is Not Weakness'
date: '2026-03-05'
category: 'essay'
excerpt: 'The world mistakes softness for surrender. It is not.'
---

Somewhere along the way, kindness got confused with naivety.

As if choosing to be gentle means you don't understand how hard the world is. As if extending grace to someone who doesn't deserve it makes you foolish rather than deliberate.

I want to argue the opposite.

Kindness, real kindness — not the performative kind, not the kind that expects something back — requires more strength than cruelty ever does. Cruelty is easy. It requires no self-awareness, no patience, no ability to hold your own pain without throwing it at someone else.

Kindness requires all of those things simultaneously.

It means someone is rude to you and you choose, consciously, not to pass it on. It means you are tired and hurting and you still notice the person next to you is tired and hurting too. It means you give without keeping score, which is perhaps the hardest thing a human being can do.

The world will call this weakness. Let it.

The world has been wrong before.
